                {{else}}
                    <a href='#' class='login-modal'>Add to your list</a>
                {{/if}}
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>Les Provinces (butcher shop)</h2>
                <h4>20 Rue d’Allergie, 75012</h4>
                <p>Last time I was in Paris, I had the chance to cook with Giovanni Passerini in his restaurant Rino (now closed). He took me here, to his butcher, where we ordered the lamb and also had a very good and juicy steak.</p>
                {{#if session.user}}
                    <a class='add-restaurant' data-id='24'>Add to your list</a>
                {{else}}
                    <a href='#' class='login-modal'>Add to your list</a>
                {{/if}}
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>L’Arpège</h2>
                <h4>84 Rue de Varenne, 75007 Paris</h4>
                <p>I was with a good friend who is a baker and we decided to do it up for lunch. I remember beautiful sweetbreads and very interesting wines by the glass. We ended around 5pm with Alain Passard sitting down at the table…now that’s a man with stature.</p>
                <p>Funny fact: they give you the knife you eat with   during your meal. I put it in my shoe to be sure not to lose it in my travels. Three months later, I was putting on the shoes for a wedding and stepped on the knife!</p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>La Boucherie Hayée</h2>
                <h4>Place d'Aligre Marché Beauvau 75012 Paris</h4>
                <p>I found a wonderful rôtisserie in Le Marché d’Aligre and had roasted pig that I ate with my fingers on a garbage can. It was so cool.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>Le Baron Rouge</h2>
                <h4>1 Rue Théophile Roussel, 75012 Paris</h4>
                <p>Continuing my journey in Le Marché D’Aligre, I had oysters at this wine bar where you drink in the street on an old wood barrel. Great wines.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>Bistrot Paul Bert</h2>
                <h4>18 Rue Paul Bert, 75011 Paris</h4>
                <p>Giovanni Passerini took me to this very French bistrot with a big bellied owner and we had wonderful snails. Unforgettable.</p>
